            <div id=3D"ti_div_Einfuehrungstext">
                <div class=3D"BeispielbildContainer"><figure><img id=3D"ti_=
img_beispiel1" src=3D"https://algorithms.discrete.ma.tum.de/graph-algorithm=
s/spp-dijkstra/img/dijkstraLR.png" alt=3D"Simple graph with 4 nodes." width=
=3D"250"></figure>
                    <p>
                        What's the shortest path from left to right?
                    </p>
                </div>

                <h1>Shortest Paths</h1><p>In many applications one wants to=
 obtain the shortest path from a to b.
                Depending on the context, the length of the path does not n=
ecessarily have to be the length in meter: One can as well look at the cost=
 of a path =E2=80=93 both if we have to pay for using it =E2=80=93 or if we=
 receive some.</p>
                <p><strong>In general we speak of cost</strong>.Therefore o=
ne assigns cost to each part of the path =E2=80=93 also called "edge".</p>
                <p>Dijkstra's Algorithm computes shortest =E2=80=93 or chea=
pest paths, if all cost are positive numbers.
                However, if one allows negative numbers, the algorithm will=
 fail.</p>
                <p>The <a href=3D"https://algorithms.discrete.ma.tum.de/gra=
ph-algorithms/spp-bellman-ford/index_de.html">Bellman-Ford Algorithm</a> by=
 contrast can also deal with negative cost.</p>

                <h1>Algorithm Idea</h1>
                <div class=3D"BeispielbildContainer">
                    <figure><img id=3D"ti_img_beispiel4_1" src=3D"https://a=
lgorithms.discrete.ma.tum.de/graph-algorithms/spp-dijkstra/img/bsp_4_1.png"=
 alt=3D"Kante vor Update" width=3D"250"><figcaption>This edge
                    is a shortcut.
                        <br>
                        We know that getting to the node on the left costs =
20
                        units. The path from the left to the right node cos=
ts
                        1 unit.</figcaption></figure>
                    <figure><img id=3D"ti_img_beispiel4_2" src=3D"https://a=
lgorithms.discrete.ma.tum.de/graph-algorithms/spp-dijkstra/img/bsp_4_2.png"=
 alt=3D"Kante vor Update" width=3D"250"><figcaption>Therefore,
                    the path to the right node costs 21 units.</figcaption>=
</figure>
                </div>
                <p> Dijkstra's algorithm computes the <strong>cost</strong>=
 of
                    the shortest paths from a given starting node to all ot=
her
                    nodes in the graph.</p>
                <p>
                  The algorithm starts at its starting node and iteratively
                    updates the current shortest paths via the current
                    node. The algorithm may, in the process, find
                    shortcuts. It continues until all edges have been visit=
ed
                    and no improvement ist possible.
                </p>
                <p>
                  The algorithm keeps the nodes that it has found, but not
                    processed yet, in a priority queue. The nodes with the
                    smallest distance to the starting point is the first no=
de
                    in the queue.
                </p>
                <p>
                    We first initialize the algorithm:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>The starting point has distance 0</strong>,=
 as
                        its distance to itself is 0.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>We don't know any path to the other nodes
                        yes</strong>, thus their <strong>cost</strong> is s=
et
                        to  <strong>infinity</strong>. During the course of
                        the algorithm, these costs will be improved. The
                        algorithm remembers the shortest path to every node=
.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        The starting node is added to the <strong>priority =
queue</strong>.
                    </li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  Next, we remove the first node from the priority queue. I=
n
                    the beginning, this will be the starting node. Then all=
 of
                    its neighbors (with their respective edges) are
                    considered. We check the following condition:
                    <strong>Is this node contained in the priority queue an=
d,
                    if so, is the edge leading to it a shortcut?</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  If this is the case, then the costs for the node
                    decrease. Otherwise, we check a second
                    condition: <strong>Has this node already been
                    visited?</strong> If the node has not been visited
                    already, then it is added to the priority queue. In the
                    future, we will inspect its neighbors as
                    well. Furthermore, its cost is set to the sum of the co=
st
                    of the edge leaving to it and the cost of its predecess=
or.
                </p>
                <p>
                  The algorithm continues until the priority queue is
                    empty. When the priority queue is empty, the algorithm =
terminates.
                </p>

                <div class=3D"BeispielbildContainer"><figure><img id=3D"ti_=
img_beispiel3" src=3D"https://algorithms.discrete.ma.tum.de/graph-algorithm=
s/spp-dijkstra/img/bsp3.png" alt=3D"Graph with distances" width=3D"250"><fi=
gcaption>The green path from
                the starting node to node b is the cheapest path. It uses 3=
 edges.</figcaption></figure>
                </div>
                <h1>Construction of the shortest path</h1>
                <p>Each time when updating the cost of some node, the algor=
ithm saves the edge that was used for the update as the <strong>predecessor=
</strong> of the node.</p>
                <p>At the end of the algorithm, the shortest path to each n=
ode can be constructed by going backwards using the predecessor edges until=
 the starting node is reached.</p>
                <p>If a node cannot be reached from the starting node, then
                    its cost stays infite.
                </p>

                <h1>What now?</h1>
