                <h3 class=3D"ui-accordion-header ui-helper-reset ui-state-d=
efault ui-accordion-header-active ui-state-active ui-corner-top ui-accordio=
n-icons" role=3D"tab" id=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-header-0" aria-contro=
ls=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-panel-0" aria-selected=3D"true" tabindex=3D=
"0"><span class=3D"ui-accordion-header-icon ui-icon ui-icon-triangle-1-s"><=
/span>What is the pseudocode of the algorithm?</h3>
                <div class=3D"ui-accordion-content ui-helper-reset ui-widge=
t-content ui-corner-bottom ui-accordion-content-active" id=3D"ui-accordion-=
tw_Accordion-panel-0" aria-labelledby=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-header-0=
" role=3D"tabpanel" aria-expanded=3D"true" aria-hidden=3D"false" style=3D"d=
isplay: block;">
                    <pre><code>Input: Weighted, directed or undirected grap=
h G=3D(V,E)=20
       using poisitive weight function l.
Output: List {d(v[j]) : j =3D 1,..,n}, containing distances dist(v[1],v[j])=
 =3D d(v[j]).</code></pre>
                    <hr>
                    <pre><code>
BEGIN
    d(v[1]) =E2=86=90 0
    FOR i =3D 2,..,n DO
        d(v[i]) =E2=86=90 =E2=88=9E, parent(v[i]) =E2=86=90 NULL
    WHILE queue =E2=89=A0 =E2=88=85 DO
        u =3D queue.extractMin()
        FOR ALL (u,w) =E2=88=88 E DO
            dist =E2=86=90 d(u) + l(u,w)
            IF w =E2=88=88 queue AND d(w) &gt; dist DO
                d(w) =3D dist, parent(w) =3D (u,w)
            ELSE IF parent(w) =3D=3D NULL THEN
                d(w) =3D dist, parent(w) =3D (u,w)
                queue.insert(w,dist)
END</code></pre>
                </div>
                <h3 class=3D"ui-accordion-header ui-helper-reset ui-state-d=
efault ui-corner-all ui-accordion-icons" role=3D"tab" id=3D"ui-accordion-tw=
_Accordion-header-1" aria-controls=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-panel-1" ar=
ia-selected=3D"false" tabindex=3D"-1"><span class=3D"ui-accordion-header-ic=
on ui-icon ui-icon-triangle-1-e"></span>How fast is the algorithm?</h3>
                <div class=3D"ui-accordion-content ui-helper-reset ui-widge=
t-content ui-corner-bottom" id=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-panel-1" aria-l=
abelledby=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-header-1" role=3D"tabpanel" aria-exp=
anded=3D"false" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"display: none;">
                    <h2>Speed of algorithms</h2>
                    <p>The speed of an algorithm is the <strong>total numbe=
r of individual steps</strong> which are performed during the execution.</p=
>
                    <p>These steps are for example:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Assignments =E2=80=93 Set distance of a node to=
 20.
                        </li>
                        <li>Comparisons =E2=80=93 Is 20 greater than 23?
                        </li>
                        <li>Comparison and assignment =E2=80=93 If 20 is gr=
eater than 15, set variable
                            <var>n</var>
                            to 20
                        </li>
                        <li>Simple Arithmetic Operations =E2=80=93 What is =
5 + 5?
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>Since it can be very difficult to count all individu=
al steps, it is desirable to only count the approximate magnitude of the nu=
mber of steps. This is also called the running time of an algorithm. Partic=
ularly, it is interesting to know the running time of an algorithm based on=
 the size of the input (in this case the number of the vertices and the edg=
es of the graph).</p>
                    <h2>Running time of Dijkstra's algorithm</h2>
                    <p>Assuming that the algorithm is run on a graph using =
<var>n</var> nodes and <m>m edges.
                    </m></p>
                    <p>
                      Every node in the graph must be inspected, thus we ne=
ed
                      at least <var>n</var> steps.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      We must extract the nodes from the priority queue bef=
ore
                      inspecting them. As extract the minimum from the
                      priority queue <var>n</var> times,we need at most <va=
r>
                      n =C2=B7 n</var> steps for this.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Nodes are added to the priority queue, when the edges
                      leaving some node are inspected. Based on the edge
                      weight, the cost of nodes in the priority queue might=
 be
                      reduced. The algorithm therefor inspects all edges th=
at
                      can be reached from the starting node. This requires
                      another <var>m</var> steps.
                    </p>
                    <p> The overall running time of the algorithm, is
                    therefore of order <var>m + n=C2=B2</var>, is we use
                    simple list as the priority queue.
                    </p>
                    <p>It is possible to improve the running time to <var>m=
 +
                    n =C2=B7 log(n)</var>. This requires a more
                    sophisticated data structure for storing the priority
                    queue (e.g. a heap).
                    </p>
                </div>
                <h3 class=3D"ui-accordion-header ui-helper-reset ui-state-d=
efault ui-corner-all ui-accordion-icons" role=3D"tab" id=3D"ui-accordion-tw=
_Accordion-header-2" aria-controls=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-panel-2" ar=
ia-selected=3D"false" tabindex=3D"-1"><span class=3D"ui-accordion-header-ic=
on ui-icon ui-icon-triangle-1-e"></span>How do we know that the algorithm w=
orks correctly?</h3>
                <div class=3D"ui-accordion-content ui-helper-reset ui-widge=
t-content ui-corner-bottom" id=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-panel-2" aria-l=
abelledby=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-header-2" role=3D"tabpanel" aria-exp=
anded=3D"false" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"display: none;">
                    <h2>A proof by contradiction</h2>
                    <p>As the algorithm expects only nonnegative edge costs=
, we can prove the following statement:<strong>All subpaths on a shortest p=
ath are also shortest paths.</strong>
                      We can prove this statement by assuming the converse:=
 There is a subpath of some shortest path, that is not a shortest path hims=
elf. In the following example. this could be the subpath between b and c, t=
hat lies on the shortest path from a to d.</p>
                    <figure class=3D"fig"><img src=3D"https://algorithms.di=
screte.ma.tum.de/graph-algorithms/spp-dijkstra/img/graph_korrekt.png" alt=
=3D"Beispielgraph" height=3D"120"></figure>
                    <p>If this subpath is not a shortest path, then there m=
ust
                    be some other path that is even shorter. This path is s=
hown with the orange arrow on the figure below . Now, there is a new path f=
rom a to d that uses the orange path between b and c. This new path must be=
 shorter than the path a-b-c-d. This, however, is a contradiction to the as=
sumtion that a-b-c-d is a shortest path.</p>
                    <figure class=3D"fig"><img src=3D"https://algorithms.di=
screte.ma.tum.de/graph-algorithms/spp-dijkstra/img/graph_korrekt_ggbsp.png"=
 alt=3D"Gegenbeispiel" height=3D"180"><figcaption>The orange arrow represen=
ts some shortest path from b to c.</figcaption></figure>
                    <p>As we have found a contradiction to the converse of =
our statement, our initial statement must hold. This implies that all paths=
 computed by our algorithm are shortest paths.</p>
                </div>
                <h3 class=3D"ui-accordion-header ui-helper-reset ui-state-d=
efault ui-corner-all ui-accordion-icons" role=3D"tab" id=3D"ui-accordion-tw=
_Accordion-header-3" aria-controls=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-panel-3" ar=
ia-selected=3D"false" tabindex=3D"-1"><span class=3D"ui-accordion-header-ic=
on ui-icon ui-icon-triangle-1-e"></span>How can we deal with negative edge =
costs?</h3>
                <div class=3D"ui-accordion-content ui-helper-reset ui-widge=
t-content ui-corner-bottom" id=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-panel-3" aria-l=
abelledby=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-header-3" role=3D"tabpanel" aria-exp=
anded=3D"false" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"display: none;">
                    <p>Exercise 3 shows that negative edge costs cause Dijk=
stra's algorithm to fail: it might not compute the shortest paths correctly=
. In the exercise, the algorithm finds a way from the stating node to node =
f with cost 4. However, a path of cost 3 exists.</p>
                    <figure class=3D"fig"><img src=3D"https://algorithms.di=
screte.ma.tum.de/graph-algorithms/spp-dijkstra/img/FA3Example.png" alt=3D"C=
ounterexample from exercise 3" height=3D"250"><figcaption>The graph from ex=
ercise 3</figcaption></figure>
                    <p>How can we deal with negative edge costs? One might =
try to add some constant to all costs, that is large enough to make all edg=
e costs positive. One could, for instance, choose the cost of the cheapest =
edge as this constant (plus 1). In the example below, the cheapest edge has=
 cost -2, thus we may add 2 (or 3) to all edge costs.

                    </p>
                    <figure class=3D"fig"><img src=3D"https://algorithms.di=
screte.ma.tum.de/graph-algorithms/spp-dijkstra/img/negativeExample.png" alt=
=3D"Negatives Beispiel" height=3D"150"><figcaption>Cheapest path from a to =
g is a-b-c-d-e-g</figcaption></figure>
                    <p>Before changing the edge costs, the shortest path fr=
om a to g was a-b-c-d-e-g, with total cost -5. After changing the edge cost=
s, the shortest path is a-f-g with total cost 6. This is problematic, as we=
 have found a completely different path than before. This example shows us,=
 that adding some constant to all edge costs cannot help us in case of nega=
tive edge costs.
                    </p>
                    <figure class=3D"fig"><img src=3D"https://algorithms.di=
screte.ma.tum.de/graph-algorithms/spp-dijkstra/img/negativeExample2.png" al=
t=3D"Counterexample with positive edge costs" height=3D"150"><figcaption>Sh=
ortest path from a to g is a-f-g</figcaption></figure>
                    <p>In order to deal with negative edge costs, we must u=
pdate some nodes that have already been visited. An algorithm that can deal=
 with this situation is the <a href=3D"https://algorithms.discrete.ma.tum.d=
e/graph-algorithms/spp-bellman-ford/index_de.html">Bellman-Ford Algorithm</=
a></p>
                </div>
                <h3 class=3D"ui-accordion-header ui-helper-reset ui-state-d=
efault ui-corner-all ui-accordion-icons" role=3D"tab" id=3D"ui-accordion-tw=
_Accordion-header-4" aria-controls=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-panel-4" ar=
ia-selected=3D"false" tabindex=3D"-1"><span class=3D"ui-accordion-header-ic=
on ui-icon ui-icon-triangle-1-e"></span>Where can I find more information a=
bout graph algorithms?</h3>
                <div class=3D"ui-accordion-content ui-helper-reset ui-widge=
t-content ui-corner-bottom" id=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-panel-4" aria-l=
abelledby=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-header-4" role=3D"tabpanel" aria-exp=
anded=3D"false" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"display: none;"><p>Other grap=
h algorithms are explained on the <a href=3D"http://www-m9.ma.tum.de/Allgem=
eines/GraphAlgorithmenEn">Website of Chair M9</a> of the TU M=C3=BCnchen.</=
p>
                <p>Furthermore there is an interesting book about shortest =
paths: <a href=3D"http://www-m9.ma.tum.de/Ruth/WebHome">Das Geheimnis des k=
=C3=BCrzesten Weges</a></p>
                <p><a href=3D"http://www.ma.tum.de/Studium/Studieninteressi=
erteEn">Studying mathematics at the TU M=C3=BCnchen</a> answers all questio=
ns about graph theory (if an answer is known).</p>
                </div>
                <h3 class=3D"ui-accordion-header ui-helper-reset ui-state-d=
efault ui-corner-all ui-accordion-icons" role=3D"tab" id=3D"ui-accordion-tw=
_Accordion-header-5" aria-controls=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-panel-5" ar=
ia-selected=3D"false" tabindex=3D"-1"><span class=3D"ui-accordion-header-ic=
on ui-icon ui-icon-triangle-1-e"></span>A last remark about this page's con=
tent, goal and citations</h3>
				<div class=3D"ui-accordion-content ui-helper-reset ui-widget-content ui=
-corner-bottom" id=3D"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-panel-5" aria-labelledby=3D=
"ui-accordion-tw_Accordion-header-5" role=3D"tabpanel" aria-expanded=3D"fal=
se" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"display: none;"><p>Chair M9 of Technische=
 Universit=C3=A4t M=C3=BCnchen does research in the fields of discrete math=
ematics, applied geometry and the mathematical optimization of applied prob=
lems. The algorithms presented on the pages at hand are very basic examples=
 for methods of discrete mathematics (the daily research conducted at the c=
hair reaches far beyond that point). These pages shall provide pupils and s=
tudents with the possibility to (better) understand and fully comprehend th=
e algorithms, which are often of importance in daily life. Therefore, the p=
resentation concentrates on the algorithms' ideas, and often explains them =
with just minimal or no mathematical notation at all.</p>
                <p>Please be advised that the pages presented here have bee=
n created within the scope of student theses, supervised by Chair M9. The c=
ode and corresponding presentation could only be tested selectively, which =
is why we cannot guarantee the complete correctness of the pages and the im=
plemented algorithms.</p>
                <p>Naturally, we are looking forward to your feedback conce=
rning the page as well as possible inaccuracies or errors. Please use the <=
a href=3D"mailto:m.ritter@ma.tum.de?subject=3DM9-Web-Feedback">suggestions =
link</a> also found in the footer.</p>
